commit.message:
Clarify the folder the plugin should be located in

The plugin needs to be in the users `Personal Lua Plugins` folder in a
directory named `cloudshark`. This updates the README so that this is a
little clearer.

Bump minor version for new release

Bump the minor version so that we can make a new release of the plugin.

Merge pull request #8 from thomasp11/master

Simplify config file creation and provide better error checking

Add information on installing cURL on Windows

Add some information and a link to the cURL Windows installer written by
Confused by Code.

Update links for more help.

Update links previously going to http://appliance.cloudshark.org to go
to https://support.cloudshark.org

Catch if user did not enter API Token

Check to see if the CLOUDSHARK_API_KEY is the default value from the
config and if it is then display an error message.

Create config file if it doesn't exist

If the cloudshark.config file does not exist create it from the
cloudshark.default file.

Display version info correctly in plugin list

This will display the version info in the Wireshark GUI when viewing the
list of plugins. It uses the set_plugin_info global utility function to
do this. To remove the configuration file from the list of installed
plugins rename this from cloudshark_init.lua to cloudshark.config.

Add support for installing into global plugin dir

This commit will search for the `cloudshark` directory first in the
personal plugins directory and if it does not exist then it will use the
global plugins directory to find the configuration file and store
temporary files.

Merge pull request #6 from guyharris/master

Clean up the installation instructions.

Clean up the installation instructions.

Don't assume what the path will be on Unix-like systems; have the user
find the path from Help -> About Wireshark first.  It is *not*
guaranteed to be in ~/.wireshark; Wireshark looks there for backwards
compatibility, but we moved the default location to ~/.config/wireshark
- see Wireshark bug 6353.

Don't assume the directory will exist; give the user instructions to
create it, on Unix-like systems, if it doesn't.

Speak of Unix-like systems in general, not just Linux or OS X - mention
*BSD, Solaris, AIX, and HP-UX as other examples.  (Feel free to add
no-longer-actively-supported UN*Xes such as IRIX or Tru64 UNIX if you
wish.)

Don't mention cloning up front - treat it and "download the zip file" as
equal possibilities, although we still mention cloning before
downloading the zip file.

This will add an empty tmp/ folder which is used to store a temporary
capture file with a new name. Once the capture is uploaded it will use
the user specified name. Fixes #3
